<br>
<br>
Let's do the math shall we?   I'm glad you asked this, because I like math and I like it when people ask me to do the math with regards to healing in PoP in relation to class balance.<br>
<br>
Generally speaking, the old cleric method of &quot;As soon as you see the berserk message, start your CH&quot; is gone with PoP, that is simply a way to ensure a dead tank.   Generally speaking, a cleric will begin a Ch at around 50% health.   With an 800hp difference between the 2 classes, 50% health will have a 400hp difference.    <br>
<br>
Making the following assumptions:  <br>
<br>
-A cleric will begin a CH at 1/2 health<br>
<br>
-The difference in 1/2 health between the theoretical warrior and knight is 400hp.  (This is assuming that Cloak of Luclin isn't being used, which would narrow the gap even further)<br>
<br>
-Also assuming BoD isn't being used (80hp/tick x 9 ticks making 720hp recovered)<br>
<br>
-Also assuming NO taps are used (Even though we know that taps = &quot;hidden hitpoints&quot;, for the sake of the requested 'doing of the math', it'd be to difficult to estimate an average interval of casting)<br>
<br>
-Also assuming a 1.5% avoidance difference (I get hit for 550ish 1.5% less times than you do based on my increased avoidance skills)<br>
<br>
-Taking a more or less standard PoP mob which hits for 550ish double, slowed, the difference in Ch intervals is approximately 11/10, meaning that for every 10 Ch's that the warrior would need, the SK would need 11.<br>
<br>
Now, the question is... is the math done?   No, it's not, and I'll tell you why it's not, because there's other factors.   <br>
<br>
- A mob can be slowed earlier into the fight with an SK than with a warrior (see Shaman's Crucible for substantiation).   This means that the mob does approximately 70% more damage to the warrior in the beginning stages of a fight than a SK, lowering the interval difference.<br>
<br>
- If a mob is pre-slowed, the warrior can and will often lose aggro, causing an ancillary heal to need to be used.  I'll get back to the ancillary heal issue, because it's the most crucial.<br>
<br>
- If a mob RESISTS slow and the warrior cannot get aggro, additional ancillary heals must be used, and even if the warrior DOES get aggro, he's still tanking an unslowed mob, vaporiing any mitigation/avoidance/hp difference, and handing the difference to the knight.<br>
<br>
Now, as for the math again, ancillary heals cost the EXACT SAME mana as complete heal, except Supernal Light which costs MORE mana han Complete heal.   I guarantee you that Supernal Remedy is cast more than once per 11 complete heals in a PoP group with a warrior as main tank.  This completely and utterly obliterates any mitigation/avoidance/HP advantage on the part of a warrior.   Generally, in my experience, Supernal Remedy is cast once for every 3ish complete heals in PoP experience groups, meaning that EVEN IF A WARRIOR HAD FULL TIME DEFENSIVE it would cost the cleric more mana to have the warrior tank than the knight.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
